ENTRY            C1873   20260115   20260312   20260312       C253
SUBENT        C1873001   20260115   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                 10         49
TITLE      Neutron detection efficiency for NE213 and BC501
           scintillators at energies between 25 and 200 MeV
AUTHOR     (R.C.Byrd, W.C.Sailor)
REFERENCE  (J,NIM/A,274,494,1989)
           #doi:10.1016/0168-9002(89)90180-0
INSTITUTE  (1USALAS)
FACILITY   (CYCLO,1USAINU) The Indiana University Cyclotron
           Facility (IUCF) (p,n) beam swinger with the cyclotron
           operating in "stripper-loop" injection mode.
SAMPLE     The 7Li targets were self-supporting rolled foils
           with thicknesses from 50 to 212 mg/cm2; the
           corresponding energy losses were 0.33-3.3 MeV.
METHOD     (EDE) A collimated dE-E telescope was placed at a 10
           degree scattering angle about 150 cm downstream from
           the target to detect scattered protons. Measurements
           were made using two different detectors placed near 0
           degree at a distance of 43.5 m from the target: BC501
           and NEA213.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-SYS) Total systematic uncertainty.
           (ERR-1) Cross section calibration using literature
           values.
           (ERR-2) Target thickness.
           (ERR-3) Detector volume.
           (ERR-4) Flight path.
           (ERR-5) Attenuation.
           (ERR-6,,1.) Charge integration.
CORRECTION a) At long flight paths large corrections must be made
           for neutron attenuation in air; values ranged from 7%
           at 200 MeV to 38% at 10 MeV. At 90, 140 and 200 MeV
           the use of copper degrader plates with thicknesses
           between 1.3 and 4.5 cm resulted in additional
           attenuation corrections of 11-32%. Various other
           materials in the flight path led to further
           corrections of 10-20%. b) The ~150 micros CAMAC
           conversion times were therefore the major cause of
           dead times, which ranged from 2% to 30% and were
           measured with negligible error. The accuracy of these
           corrections is best demonstrated by the 1% agreement
           between the measured and calculated copper
           attenuation values, despite dead time corrections of
           up to 50% due to the high proton counting rates when
           the plates were removed. c) The accuracy is best
           discussed by separating effects due to the flux and
           shape calibrations. For the shape uncertainties, even
           with the corrections for nonlinearity the uncertainty
           in the 6 MeV threshold is only about 1.5 MeV,
           which increases the uncertainty in the efficiency by
           7.7% at 30 MeV and 4.3% at 200 MeV.
HISTORY    (20260115C) BP
ENDBIB              49
COMMON               5          3
ANG        ERR-2      ERR-3      ERR-4      ERR-5
ADEG       PER-CENT   PER-CENT   PER-CENT   PER-CENT
         0.        1.6         6.         1.         2.
ENDCOMMON            3
ENDSUBENT           56
SUBENT        C1873002   20260115   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                  3         11
REACTION   (3-LI-7(P,X)0-NN-1,,DA/DE)
DETECTOR   (SCIN) BC scintillator: It consisted of a cylinder
           20.3 cm deep and 30.5 cm in diameter, filled with
           BC501 scintillator to leave an expansion void 2.5% of
           the scintillator's volume. The scintillator was
           optically coupled to a 12.7 cm diameter RCA4522
           photomultiplier tube through a conical light guide
           9.9 cm long and 11.0 cm in final diameter. The
           specified density and hydrogen/carbon ratio for the
           for BC501 are 0.901 and 1.287.
STATUS     (CURVE,,R.C.Byrd+,J,NIM/A,274,494,1989) Fig. 1
ENDBIB              11
NOCOMMON             0          0
